}}\n'''Jitendra Kumar Barnwal''' is an Indian politician from Jharkhand. He contesting from Godda in Lok Sabha elections and Deoghar in Jharkhand election from [[Marxist Co-ordination Committee]].<ref name=\"Myneta\">{{cite web|url=http://myneta.info/LokSabha2019/candidate.php?candidate_id=14091|title=Jitendra Kumar Barnwal - Independent|work=Myneta}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://myneta.info/jharkhand2019/candidate.php?candidate_id=12319|title=Jitendra Kumar Barnwal - Marxist Co-ordination Committee|work=Myneta|date=2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBarnwal was born in 1985 in Jharkhand. His father name is Shiv Shankar Barnwal. He is a Business person.<ref name=\"Myneta\"/>\n\n==Political career==\nHe contesting from Godda in Lok Sabha elections independently<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amarujala.com/election/lok-sabha-elections/jharkhand/candidates/jitendra-kumar-barnwal-ind-2019-godda-3-jharkhand|title=Jitendra Kumar Barnwal: Godda Election Result|work=[[Amar Ujala]]}}</ref> and Deoghar in Jharkhand election from [[Marxist Co-ordination Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/jitendra-kumar-barnwal/candidates/candidateid-14091.cms|title=Jitendra Kumar Barnwal|work=[[The Economic Times]]|date=2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jitendra_Kumar_Barnwal"}
{"title_page": "Needham B. Broughton High School", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date = May 2016}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name                   = Needham B. Broughton High School\n|image                  = Needham_B._Broughton_High_School_logo.jpg\n|image_size             = 200px\n|streetaddress          = 723 St. Mary's Street\n|city                   = [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]]\n|state                  = [[North Carolina]]\n|zipcode                = 27605\n|country                = United States\n|coordinates            = {{coord|35.7902|-78.6524|region:US-NC_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n|schooltype             = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|established            = 1929\n|us_nces_school_id= {{NCES School ID|370472001839|school_name=Needham Broughton High|access_date=October 11, 2012}} \n|principal              = Elena Ashburn\n|teaching_staff         = 124.61 ([[Full-time equivalent|FTE]])<ref name=NCES></ref>\n|ratio                  = 17.21<ref name=NCES></ref>\n|enrollment             = 2,144 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=3704720&SchoolPageNum=8&ID=370472001839Needham Broughton High]</ref>\n|schedule               =\n|hours_in_day           = Monday-Friday, 7:25 A.M-2:18 P.M\n|fight_song             = Cheer Broughton\n|sports                 = 18 varsity teams\n|nickname               = Capitals\n|rival                  = [[William G. Enloe High School]]\n|yearbook               = ''The Latipac''<ref>[https://archive.org/details/latipac19371937need The Latipac &#91;1937&#93;] by Needham B. Broughton High School</ref>\n|information            = \n|website                = {{URL|broughton.wcpss.net}}\n|footnotes              =\n|schedule_type          = Modified Block, 4-period (A-B Day)\n|colors                 = Purple and Gold<br />\n|free_label             = Degrees\n|free_text              = [[IB Diploma Programme|IB Diploma]]\n|free_label1            = Programs\n|free_text1             = [[IB Diploma Programme|IB Programme]]\n|pushpin_map            = North Carolina#USA\n}}\n\n[[File:Broughton High School June 2007.jpg|thumb|right]]\n\n'''Needham B. Broughton High School''', commonly known as '''Broughton High School''', is one of the flagship schools of the [[Wake County Public School System]]. It is located at 723 St. Mary's Street, [[Raleigh, North Carolina]], United States. Broughton is the only Global Studies Magnet high school in Wake County, and the school offers the International Baccalaureate Diploma Programme. Broughton was named after the Raleigh businessman and politician, [[Needham B. Broughton]], who contributed much to the public schools of the area. Broughton was ranked 690th in ''[[Newsweek]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s list of the top United States schools in 2007.<ref name=\"NWTS\">{{cite news|title=The Complete List of the 1,000 Top U.S.Schools|work=[[Newsweek]]|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/8759025/site/newsweek/page/4/|date=August 5, 2005|accessdate=January 14, 2007 |url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070109163318/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/8759025/site/newsweek/page/4/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = January 9, 2007}}</ref> It runs on a [[block scheduling|4x4 modified block schedule]] (A Day-B Day which allows students to go a whole semester without missing a \"core class\" or a foreign language).  Broughton is known for its castle-like stone facade and tall bell tower. The architect was William Henley Deitrick, [[FAIA]].<ref name=\"Profile Doc\">[http://broughton.wcpss.net/modules/mastop_publish/files/files_4abcf5955f2e1.pdf Profile Doc]</ref>\n\n==History==\nNeedham B. Broughton High School was established in 1929 as Raleigh High School. It is the oldest high school in Raleigh still being used.<ref>{{cite book| last = Anderson| first = Norman D.| last2 = Fowler| first2 = B. T.| title = Raleigh: North Carolina's Capital City on Postcards| publisher = Arcadia Publishing| series = Images of America| edition = illustrated| date = 1996| pages = 87| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=D7gA02OTaewC| isbn = 9780738568720}}</ref> Shortly after it was built, C. B. Edwards sent a letter to the Raleigh Public School Board, requesting that the school be named for [[Needham B. Broughton]] in honor of his service to public education in the city. The renaming ceremony took place in 1930, towards the end of the school year.<ref>{{cite book| last = Barbee| first = Jennie M| title = Historical sketches of the Raleigh Public Schools, 1876-1941-1942| publisher = Barbee Pupils' Association| date = 1943| location = [[Raleigh]], [[North Carolina]]| url = https://archive.org/details/historicalsketch00barb| oclc= 7343710|page=[https://archive.org/details/historicalsketch00barb/page/67 67]}}</ref>\n\n== Racial controversies ==\nBroughton was originally an all white segregated school.<ref>{{cite book| title = U.S. News & World Report| publisher = U.S. News Publishing Corporation| volume = 97| date = 1984| pages = 194| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=l3TuAAAAMAAJ&q=Needham+B.+Broughton+High+School+segregation}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018 there was controversy at the school when two students posted racist comments over social media, one of them making incendiary remarks about the student body of [[William G. Enloe High School]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/education/article197207069.html| title = 2 Wake County high school students make racist comments in videos| last = Pressley| first = Baird| date = January 29, 2018| website = [[The News & Observer]]}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nBroughton offers 16 [[Advanced Placement]] (AP) courses as well as 28 [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) courses. The school offers four foreign languages: French, German,  Mandarin and Spanish.  Broughton has produced eight [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] [[Scholarships of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|Morehead-Cain Scholars]], three [[North Carolina State University]] Park Scholars, and one [[Wake Forest University]] Reynolds Scholar.<ref name=\"Profile Doc\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://broughton.wcpss.net/modules/mastop_publish/?tac=IB_Information |title=Broughton High School \u2013 IB Information |publisher=Broughton.wcpss.net |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nBroughton's sports teams play under the name \"Capitals\", sometimes shortened to \"Caps\".<ref name= caps>{{cite news| last = Justice| first = David| date = February 2, 2016| title = Broughton's boys, Enloe's girls split Cap-8 basketball victories| url = http://www.newsobserver.com/sports/high-school/article59464073.html| newspaper = [[The News & Observer]]| location = Raleigh, NC| access-date = May 20, 2016}}</ref> The school has 18 varsity teams (the newest of which are the lacrosse and gymnastic teams) that compete with other 4A schools in the Cap-7 Conference and with schools around the state.<ref>[http://www.broughtonathletics.com/index-old.html Broughton Athletics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Broughton's main sports facilities are the 3,000-seat Capital Stadium and the Holliday Gymnasium.  In 2013, Broughton finished second in the Under Armor Finding Undeniable competition, which is a $140,000 prize toward a high school athletic program.\n\nBroughton's historical rival is [[William G. Enloe High School]].<ref name= caps/><ref>{{cite news| editor-last = Fader| editor-first = Stephanie| date         = October 1968| title = AYCOCK AIDS JAYVEES| url  = http://www.enloe1969.com/000/7/6/3/11367/userfiles/file/The_Eagles_Eye_(October_1968).pdf| newspaper = The Eagle's Eye| location     = Raleigh, NC| access-date  = May 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://article.wn.com/view/2013/11/02/Broughton_tops_longtime_rival_Enloe_with_a_field_goal/| title = Broughton tops long-time rival Enloe with a field goal| date = November 2, 2011| website = article.wn.com| publisher = [[The News & Observer]]| access-date = May 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Arts==\nBroughton has a band, orchestra, chorus, and dance program, among other groups. The \"Carolina Spirit\" show choir was known as the top show choir in the country during the 1990s, winning six consecutive Showstoppers National/International Championships.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} In 2007 the drama department produced [[Lorraine Hansberry]]'s 1959 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] play ''[[A Raisin in the Sun]]''. In 2015 the drama team put on [[The Ugly Duckling]] at the Scotland Theater Festival.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://broughton.wcpss.net/studentlife/clubs/index.shtml Broughton High School Clubs and Organizations]</ref>\n\n===Band===\nBroughton's award-winning band program has attended the [[Tournament of Roses Parade|2008 and 2012 Tournament of Roses Parades]].<ref>[http://media.roseparade.net/mediaGuideBand.asp?id=759 Pasadena Tournament of Roses Website-Media]</ref> The 186 member band was one of fifteen bands selected to participate for the 2008 parade, and one of only six high schools.<ref>[http://www.tournamentofroses.com/roseparade/participants.asp Tournament of Roses Parade Participants] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218053226/http://www.tournamentofroses.com/roseparade/participants.asp |date=December 18, 2008 }}</ref> They were invited to march at the Inaugural Parade for N.C. Governor [[Bev Perdue]]. The Jazz I group also performed for President [[Barack Obama]] during his visit to Raleigh on July 29, 2009. Broughton also has a concert band, a symphonic wind ensemble, and a jazz band that performed for Jay Leno in 2011 and has made other appearances in Raleigh's \"Pieces of Gold\" at Memorial Auditorium, and played in Cameron Village's Chick-fil-A and Noodles restaurants.{{citation needed|date= October 2016}}\n\n===Publications===\nBroughton's publications program includes the annual yearbook and newspaper. The yearbook is named the \"Latipac\" which is \"Capital\" (Broughton's mascot)spelled backwards. The school newspaper, the \"Hi-Times\", is published and distributed several times a year.\n\n===Dance===\nStudents from Broughton's Dance Program regularly perform throughout the country and at arts functions around the state. They put on several concerts each year, including a benefit concert in December which is completely produced by the Broughton Dance Company. In 2017, the Broughton Dance Director, Betsy Graves, was named Wake County Public School System Teacher of the Year.<ref>https://www.wcpss.net/Page/30618</ref>{{better source|date=February 2019}}\n\n==Community service==\nStudents are required to perform 25 hours of service each year within the community. Students can also participate in service trips to [[Guatemala]] (Proyecto Quetzal) and in projects such as a school-sponsored [[Habitat for Humanity]] house.<ref name=\"publicschoolreview.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.publicschoolreview.com/school_ov/school_id/60616 |title=Needham Broughton High School \u2013 Raleigh, North Carolina/NC \u2013 Public School Profile |publisher=Publicschoolreview.com |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>\n<ref>[http://broughton.wcpss.net/modules/info/?tac=community_service Broughton High School \u2013 Community Service Program]</ref>\n\n===Technology===\nBroughton is serviced by the adjacent Wade Edwards Learning Lab (WELL),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wade.org/ |title=Wade Edwards Learning Lab |publisher=Wade.org |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref> a program established by former Senator [[John Edwards]] that provides after-school access to computers. Broughton's graphics department has also received an update.\n\nFrom 2002 to 2004 Broughton underwent a $14&nbsp;million renovation in which much of the school was gutted and refitted with state-of-the-art technology and new interiors. During the 2004\u20132005 school year Broughton received an additional $5&nbsp;million to renovate its Holliday Gymnasium (the state's largest high school gym). One of the highlights of the renovations was the refurbishment of the newly titled Diane Payne Auditorium, named after the retired veteran principal.<ref name=\"broughton.wcpss.net\">{{cite web|url=http://broughton.wcpss.net/modules/mastop_publish/?tac=Administration |title=Broughton High School \u2013 Broughton Administration |publisher=Broughton.wcpss.net |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"publicschoolreview.com\"/>\n\n===WCAP===\nBroughton broadcasts its morning announcements via a closed-circuit network, headquartered from the WCAP media studio in the library. WCAP was founded in 1992 as a monthly, pre-recorded news production informing students of events happening around Broughton. By 1993 it had become a live, daily show broadcast from the media center. The set has undergone many renovations throughout the years, and WCAP celebrated its twentieth birthday on January 30, 2012.<ref>[http://www.wcaptv.com/ Needham B. Broughton's WCAP Website]</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://broughton.wcpss.net/wcap/ |title=WCAP |publisher=Broughton.wcpss.net |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe music video for the 1993 song \"[['74\u2013'75]]\" by [[The Connells]] features members of the Broughton High School Class of 1975 as they appeared in 1993 with juxtaposed images of their senior pictures.<ref>[http://onesimpleband.net/Videos.html One Simple Band website \u2013 The Connells videos]. Retrieved January 21, 2012</ref> An update to the video was done in 2015.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p6l3Lh2cb_g 2015 update of the Connells' '74\u2013'75 video clip]. Retrieved February 21, 2016</ref>\nBand members of The Connells who graduated from Broughton are bassist David Connell and former drummer for The Connells, Peele Wimberly.\n\nBroughton High School is featured heavily in the popular satirical website ITB Insider, written primarily under the pseudonym of William Needham Finley IV (the middle name, Needham, echoing the first name in the full Needham Broughton High School).<ref>http://www.itbinsider.com/?s=broughton</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2008}}\n<!-- Please keep this list in alphabetical order by last name.  Also, please try not to add names without a Wikipedia article.  Redlinked names will eventually be deleted.-->\n\n*[[Juston Burris]], current [[cornerback]] for the [[Cleveland Browns]]\n*[[John W. Coffey]], author, art historian, Deputy Director for Collections at the [[North Carolina Museum of Art]]\n*[[Junius Coston]], football player for the [[Green Bay Packers]]\n*[[The Connells|David Connell]], bassist for pop rock group [[The Connells]]\n*[[Allison Dahle]], Member of the [[North Carolina House of Representatives]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allisonforhouse.com/about-allison-1|title=About Allison|website=Allison for House|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref>\n*[[Troop 41|Lelynd Darkes]], rapper\n*[[Aubrey Dollar]], actress and sister of Caroline\n*[[Caroline Dollar]], actress and sister of Aubrey\n*[[Cate Edwards]], daughter of former Sen. [[John Edwards]]\n*[[Jim Farmer (runner)|Jim Farmer]], former long-distance track runner\n*[[Colin Fickes]], actor\n*[[Devonte Graham]], current basketball player for the [[Charlotte Hornets]]\n*[[Scott Goodwin]], former professional soccer player\n*[[Scott Hoch]], professional golfer and [[Ryder Cup]] member\n*[[Richard Jenrette]], [[Wall Street]] businessman and co-founder of the [[Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette]] firm\n*[[Bj\u00f8rn Johnsen]], professional soccer player for [[AZ Alkmaar]]\n*[[Lauren Kennedy]], Broadway actress\n*[[Forrest Lasso]], current soccer player for [[FC Cincinnati]]\n*[[Sharon Lawrence]], ''[[NYPD Blue]]'' actress\n*[[Pete Maravich]], former [[LSU Tigers basketball|LSU]] and [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] basketball player; (also attended [[D. W. Daniel High School]])\n*[[Burley Mitchell]], former Chief Justice of the [[North Carolina Supreme Court]]\n*[[Casey Nogueira]], [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina]] soccer forward,<ref>[http://tarheelblue.cstv.com/sports/w-soccer/mtt/nogueira_casey00.html UNC Biography]</ref> Member U.S. women's U-20 soccer team<ref>[http://www.ussoccer.com/teams/u-20-wnt/n/casey-nogueira.aspx U.S. Soccer Website \u2013 Player Bio]</ref>\n*[[Oscar F. Peatross]], highly decorated Major general in the Marine Corps\n*[[Reynolds Price]], writer and [[National Public Radio|NPR]] radio host\n*[[Shavlik Randolph]], [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke University]] and [[Boston Celtics]] basketball player\n*[[Jerome Robinson]], former basketball player at [[Boston College]] and current player for the [[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n*[[Hunter Schafer]], model, actress, and LGBT rights activist, known for her role in the [[HBO]] television series ''[[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]''\n*[[Jeremy Shelley]], former kicker for the [[Alabama football|University of Alabama]] football team, currently an NFL free agent\n*[[Webb Simpson]], [[PGA Tour]] golfer and [[2012 U.S. Open (golf)|2012 US Open]] Champion\n*[[Phil Spence]], [[NC State Wolfpack men's basketball|NC State]] basketball player and former head coach at [[North Carolina Central University]]<ref>[http://www.gopack.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/071400aaa.html NCCU Names Spence Men's Basketball Head Coach]</ref>\n*[[Anne Tyler]], [[Pulitzer Prize for fiction|Pulitzer Prize]]-winning author\n*[[Hubertus van der Vaart]], [[Dutch American]] businessman, [[Rhodes Scholarship|Rhodes Scholar]], and Co-founder/Chairman of [[Small Enterprise Assistance Funds|SEAF]] (Small Enterprise Assistance Funds)\n*[[Donald van der Vaart]], former Secretary of the [[North Carolina Department of Environmental Quality]], lawyer and engineer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/business/article42125817.html |title=NC's new environmental regulator is polarizing figure |publisher=The News & Observer |date=October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Jesse Williams (athlete)|Jesse Williams]], high jumper in the U.S. Olympic team in Beijing (2008), gold medalist at the 2011 World Championships in Daegu, South Korea<ref name=\"Clarey\">{{cite web|last=Clarey|first=Christopher|title=World Championships \u2013 Americans Strike Gold in Unexpected Places|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/02/sports/02iht-ATHLETICS02.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|United States|Schools}}\n*{{official website|http://broughton.wcpss.net}}\n*[http://www.broughtonathletics.com Broughton Athletics website]\n\n{{Wake County, North Carolina Schools}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Broughton, Needham B.}}\n[[Category:Wake County Public School System]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1929]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Schools in Raleigh, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Magnet schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:1929 establishments in North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date = May 2016}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name                   = Needham B. Broughton High School\n|image                  = Needham_B._Broughton_High_School_logo.jpg\n|image_size             = 200px\n|streetaddress          = 723 St. Mary's Street\n|city                   = [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]]\n|state                  = [[North Carolina]]\n|zipcode                = 27605\n|country                = United States\n|coordinates            = {{coord|35.7902|-78.6524|region:US-NC_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n|schooltype             = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|established            = 1929\n|us_nces_school_id= {{NCES School ID|370472001839|school_name=Needham Broughton High|access_date=October 11, 2012}} \n|principal              = Elena Ashburn\n|teaching_staff         = 124.61 ([[Full-time equivalent|FTE]])<ref name=NCES></ref>\n|ratio                  = 17.21<ref name=NCES></ref>\n|enrollment             = 2,144 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=3704720&SchoolPageNum=8&ID=370472001839Needham Broughton High]</ref>\n|schedule               =\n|hours_in_day           = Monday-Friday, 7:25 A.M-2:18 P.M\n|fight_song             = Cheer Broughton\n|sports                 = 18 varsity teams\n|nickname               = Capitals\n|rival                  = [[William G. Enloe High School]]\n|yearbook               = ''The Latipac''<ref>[https://archive.org/details/latipac19371937need The Latipac &#91;1937&#93;] by Needham B. Broughton High School</ref>\n|information            = \n|website                = {{URL|broughton.wcpss.net}}\n|footnotes              =\n|schedule_type          = Modified Block, 4-period (A-B Day)\n|colors                 = Purple and Gold<br />\n|free_label             = Degrees\n|free_text              = [[IB Diploma Programme|IB Diploma]]\n|free_label1            = Programs\n|free_text1             = [[IB Diploma Programme|IB Programme]]\n|pushpin_map            = North Carolina#USA\n}}\n\n[[File:Broughton High School June 2007.jpg|thumb|right]]\n\n'''Needham B. Broughton High School''', commonly known as '''Broughton High School''', is one of the flagship schools of the [[Wake County Public School System]]. It is located at 723 St. Mary's Street, [[Raleigh, North Carolina]], United States. Broughton is the only Global Studies Magnet high school in Wake County, and the school offers the International Baccalaureate Diploma Programme. Broughton was named after the Raleigh businessman and politician, [[Needham B. Broughton]], who contributed much to the public schools of the area. Broughton was ranked 690th in ''[[Newsweek]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s list of the top United States schools in 2007.<ref name=\"NWTS\">{{cite news|title=The Complete List of the 1,000 Top U.S.Schools|work=[[Newsweek]]|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/8759025/site/newsweek/page/4/|date=August 5, 2005|accessdate=January 14, 2007 |url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070109163318/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/8759025/site/newsweek/page/4/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = January 9, 2007}}</ref> It runs on a [[block scheduling|4x4 modified block schedule]] (A Day-B Day which allows students to go a whole semester without missing a \"core class\" or a foreign language).  Broughton is known for its castle-like stone facade and tall bell tower. The architect was William Henley Deitrick, [[FAIA]].<ref name=\"Profile Doc\">[http://broughton.wcpss.net/modules/mastop_publish/files/files_4abcf5955f2e1.pdf Profile Doc]</ref>\n\n==History==\nNeedham B. Broughton High School was established in 1929 as Raleigh High School. It is the oldest high school in Raleigh still being used.<ref>{{cite book| last = Anderson| first = Norman D.| last2 = Fowler| first2 = B. T.| title = Raleigh: North Carolina's Capital City on Postcards| publisher = Arcadia Publishing| series = Images of America| edition = illustrated| date = 1996| pages = 87| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=D7gA02OTaewC| isbn = 9780738568720}}</ref> Shortly after it was built, C. B. Edwards sent a letter to the Raleigh Public School Board, requesting that the school be named for [[Needham B. Broughton]] in honor of his service to public education in the city. The renaming ceremony took place in 1930, towards the end of the school year.<ref>{{cite book| last = Barbee| first = Jennie M| title = Historical sketches of the Raleigh Public Schools, 1876-1941-1942| publisher = Barbee Pupils' Association| date = 1943| location = [[Raleigh]], [[North Carolina]]| url = https://archive.org/details/historicalsketch00barb| oclc= 7343710|page=[https://archive.org/details/historicalsketch00barb/page/67 67]}}</ref>\n\n== Racial controversies ==\nBroughton was originally an all white segregated school.<ref>{{cite book| title = U.S. News & World Report| publisher = U.S. News Publishing Corporation| volume = 97| date = 1984| pages = 194| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=l3TuAAAAMAAJ&q=Needham+B.+Broughton+High+School+segregation}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018 there was controversy at the school when two students posted racist comments over social media, one of them making incendiary remarks about the student body of [[William G. Enloe High School]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/education/article197207069.html| title = 2 Wake County high school students make racist comments in videos| last = Pressley| first = Baird| date = January 29, 2018| website = [[The News & Observer]]}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nBroughton offers 16 [[Advanced Placement]] (AP) courses as well as 28 [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) courses. The school offers four foreign languages: French, German,  Mandarin and Spanish.  Broughton has produced eight [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] [[Scholarships of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|Morehead-Cain Scholars]], three [[North Carolina State University]] Park Scholars, and one [[Wake Forest University]] Reynolds Scholar.<ref name=\"Profile Doc\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://broughton.wcpss.net/modules/mastop_publish/?tac=IB_Information |title=Broughton High School \u2013 IB Information |publisher=Broughton.wcpss.net |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nBroughton's sports teams play under the name \"Capitals\", sometimes shortened to \"Caps\".<ref name= caps>{{cite news| last = Justice| first = David| date = February 2, 2016| title = Broughton's boys, Enloe's girls split Cap-8 basketball victories| url = http://www.newsobserver.com/sports/high-school/article59464073.html| newspaper = [[The News & Observer]]| location = Raleigh, NC| access-date = May 20, 2016}}</ref> The school has 18 varsity teams (the newest of which are the lacrosse and gymnastic teams) that compete with other 4A schools in the Cap-7 Conference and with schools around the state.<ref>[http://www.broughtonathletics.com/index-old.html Broughton Athletics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Broughton's main sports facilities are the 3,000-seat Capital Stadium and the Holliday Gymnasium.  In 2013, Broughton finished second in the Under Armor Finding Undeniable competition, which is a $140,000 prize toward a high school athletic program.\n\nBroughton's historical rival is [[William G. Enloe High School]].<ref name= caps/><ref>{{cite news| editor-last = Fader| editor-first = Stephanie| date         = October 1968| title = AYCOCK AIDS JAYVEES| url  = http://www.enloe1969.com/000/7/6/3/11367/userfiles/file/The_Eagles_Eye_(October_1968).pdf| newspaper = The Eagle's Eye| location     = Raleigh, NC| access-date  = May 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://article.wn.com/view/2013/11/02/Broughton_tops_longtime_rival_Enloe_with_a_field_goal/| title = Broughton tops long-time rival Enloe with a field goal| date = November 2, 2011| website = article.wn.com| publisher = [[The News & Observer]]| access-date = May 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Arts==\nBroughton has a band, orchestra, chorus, and dance program, among other groups. The \"Carolina Spirit\" show choir was known as the top show choir in the country during the 1990s, winning six consecutive Showstoppers National/International Championships.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} In 2007 the drama department produced [[Lorraine Hansberry]]'s 1959 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] play ''[[A Raisin in the Sun]]''. In 2015 the drama team put on [[The Ugly Duckling]] at the Scotland Theater Festival.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://broughton.wcpss.net/studentlife/clubs/index.shtml Broughton High School Clubs and Organizations]</ref>\n\n===Band===\nBroughton's award-winning band program has attended the [[Tournament of Roses Parade|2008 and 2012 Tournament of Roses Parades]].<ref>[http://media.roseparade.net/mediaGuideBand.asp?id=759 Pasadena Tournament of Roses Website-Media]</ref> The 186 member band was one of fifteen bands selected to participate for the 2008 parade, and one of only six high schools.<ref>[http://www.tournamentofroses.com/roseparade/participants.asp Tournament of Roses Parade Participants] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218053226/http://www.tournamentofroses.com/roseparade/participants.asp |date=December 18, 2008 }}</ref> They were invited to march at the Inaugural Parade for N.C. Governor [[Bev Perdue]]. The Jazz I group also performed for President [[Barack Obama]] during his visit to Raleigh on July 29, 2009. Broughton also has a concert band, a symphonic wind ensemble, and a jazz band that performed for Jay Leno in 2011 and has made other appearances in Raleigh's \"Pieces of Gold\" at Memorial Auditorium, and played in Cameron Village's Chick-fil-A and Noodles restaurants.{{citation needed|date= October 2016}}\n\n===Publications===\nBroughton's publications program includes the annual yearbook and newspaper. The yearbook is named the \"Latipac\" which is \"Capital\" (Broughton's mascot)spelled backwards. The school newspaper, the \"Hi-Times\", is published and distributed several times a year.\n\n===Dance===\nStudents from Broughton's Dance Program regularly perform throughout the country and at arts functions around the state. They put on several concerts each year, including a benefit concert in December which is completely produced by the Broughton Dance Company. In 2017, the Broughton Dance Director, Betsy Graves, was named Wake County Public School System Teacher of the Year.<ref>https://www.wcpss.net/Page/30618</ref>{{better source|date=February 2019}}\n\n==Community service==\nStudents are required to perform 25 hours of service each year within the community. Students can also participate in service trips to [[Guatemala]] (Proyecto Quetzal) and in projects such as a school-sponsored [[Habitat for Humanity]] house.<ref name=\"publicschoolreview.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.publicschoolreview.com/school_ov/school_id/60616 |title=Needham Broughton High School \u2013 Raleigh, North Carolina/NC \u2013 Public School Profile |publisher=Publicschoolreview.com |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>\n<ref>[http://broughton.wcpss.net/modules/info/?tac=community_service Broughton High School \u2013 Community Service Program]</ref>\n\n===Technology===\nBroughton is serviced by the adjacent Wade Edwards Learning Lab (WELL),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wade.org/ |title=Wade Edwards Learning Lab |publisher=Wade.org |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref> a program established by former Senator [[John Edwards]] that provides after-school access to computers. Broughton's graphics department has also received an update.\n\nFrom 2002 to 2004 Broughton underwent a $14&nbsp;million renovation in which much of the school was gutted and refitted with state-of-the-art technology and new interiors. During the 2004\u20132005 school year Broughton received an additional $5&nbsp;million to renovate its Holliday Gymnasium (the state's largest high school gym). One of the highlights of the renovations was the refurbishment of the newly titled Diane Payne Auditorium, named after the retired veteran principal.<ref name=\"broughton.wcpss.net\">{{cite web|url=http://broughton.wcpss.net/modules/mastop_publish/?tac=Administration |title=Broughton High School \u2013 Broughton Administration |publisher=Broughton.wcpss.net |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"publicschoolreview.com\"/>\n\n===WCAP===\nBroughton broadcasts its morning announcements via a closed-circuit network, headquartered from the WCAP media studio in the library. WCAP was founded in 1992 as a monthly, pre-recorded news production informing students of events happening around Broughton. By 1993 it had become a live, daily show broadcast from the media center. The set has undergone many renovations throughout the years, and WCAP celebrated its twentieth birthday on January 30, 2012.<ref>[http://www.wcaptv.com/ Needham B. Broughton's WCAP Website]</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://broughton.wcpss.net/wcap/ |title=WCAP |publisher=Broughton.wcpss.net |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe music video for the 1993 song \"[['74\u2013'75]]\" by [[The Connells]] features members of the Broughton High School Class of 1975 as they appeared in 1993 with juxtaposed images of their senior pictures.<ref>[http://onesimpleband.net/Videos.html One Simple Band website \u2013 The Connells videos]. Retrieved January 21, 2012</ref> An update to the video was done in 2015.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p6l3Lh2cb_g 2015 update of the Connells' '74\u2013'75 video clip]. Retrieved February 21, 2016</ref>\nBand members of The Connells who graduated from Broughton are bassist David Connell and former drummer for The Connells, Peele Wimberly.\n\nBroughton High School is featured heavily in the popular satirical website ITB Insider, written primarily under the pseudonym of William Needham Finley IV (the middle name, Needham, echoing the first name in the full Needham Broughton High School).<ref>http://www.itbinsider.com/?s=broughton</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2008}}\n<!-- Please keep this list in alphabetical order by last name.  Also, please try not to add names without a Wikipedia article.  Redlinked names will eventually be deleted.-->\n\n*[[Juston Burris]], current [[cornerback]] for the [[Cleveland Browns]]\n*[[John W. Coffey]], author, art historian, Deputy Director for Collections at the [[North Carolina Museum of Art]]\n*[[Junius Coston]], football player for the [[Green Bay Packers]]\n*[[The Connells|David Connell]], bassist for pop rock group [[The Connells]]\n*[[Allison Dahle]], Member of the [[North Carolina House of Representatives]]<ref