Schafer]], model, actress, and LGBT rights activist, known for her role in the [[HBO]] television series [[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]\n*[[Jeremy Shelley]], former kicker for the [[Alabama football|University of Alabama]] football team, currently an NFL free agent\n*[[Webb Simpson]], [[PGA Tour]] golfer and [[2012 U.S. Open (golf)|2012 US Open]] Champion\n*[[Phil Spence]], [[NC State Wolfpack men's basketball|NC State]] basketball player and former head coach at [[North Carolina Central University]]<ref>[http://www.gopack.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/071400aaa.html NCCU Names Spence Men's Basketball Head Coach]</ref>\n*[[Anne Tyler]], [[Pulitzer Prize for fiction|Pulitzer Prize]]-winning author\n*[[Hubertus van der Vaart]], [[Dutch American]] businessman, [[Rhodes Scholarship|Rhodes Scholar]], and Co-founder/Chairman of [[Small Enterprise Assistance Funds|SEAF]] (Small Enterprise Assistance Funds)\n*[[Donald van der Vaart]], former Secretary of the [[North Carolina Department of Environmental Quality]], lawyer and engineer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/business/article42125817.html |title=NC's new environmental regulator is polarizing figure |publisher=The News & Observer |date=October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Jesse Williams (athlete)|Jesse Williams]], high jumper in the U.S. Olympic team in Beijing (2008), gold medalist at the 2011 World Championships in Daegu, South Korea<ref name=\"Clarey\">{{cite web|last=Clarey|first=Christopher|title=World Championships \u2013 Americans Strike Gold in Unexpected Places|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/02/sports/02iht-ATHLETICS02.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|United States|Schools}}\n*{{official website|http://broughton.wcpss.net}}\n*[http://www.broughtonathletics.com Broughton Athletics website]\n\n{{Wake County, North Carolina Schools}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Broughton, Needham B.}}\n[[Category:Wake County Public School System]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1929]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Schools in Raleigh, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Magnet schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:1929 establishments in North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Jamie7687", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable alumni:formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Needham_B._Broughton_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Karol G", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Giraldo|Navarro}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Karol G\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Carolina Giraldo Navarro\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1991|2|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Medell\u00edn]], Colombia\n| parents          = Guillermo Giraldo\n| image            = Karol G Telemedell\u00edn.jpg\n| caption          = Karol G in 2018\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Urbano music|Urbano]]|[[reggaeton]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/06/21/pongan-atencin-the-queens-of-latin-urbans-past-present-and-future|title=Pongan Atenci\u00f3n: The Queens Of Latin Urban\u2019s Past, Present And Future|work=The FADER|accessdate=2017-09-07|language=en}}</ref>}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter}}\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| label            = [[Universal Music Latin Entertainment|Universal Latin]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|karolgmusic.com}}\n}}\n'''Carolina Giraldo Navarro''' (born 14 February 1991),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://lasvegasweekly.com/nightlife/industry-weekly/2017/feb/08/karol-g-reggaeton-embassy-nightclub-las-vegas/|title=Rising reggaeton star Karol G visits latin nightlife hot spot Embassy|work=LasVegasWeekly.com|access-date=2017-09-07}}</ref> known professionally as '''Karol G''', is a Colombian [[reggaeton]] singer and songwriter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uproxx.com/music/karol-g-casi-nada-acoustic-uncharted/|title=Karol G's Acoustic Performance Of 'Casi Nada' Proves She's A Star|date=2016-10-17|work=UPROXX|access-date=2017-09-07|language=en-US}}</ref> Her collaboration with Puerto Rican singer/rapper [[Bad Bunny]] \"Ahora Me Llama\" made her career breakthrough in the Latin community. Collaborations with her partner [[Anuel AA]] have been some highlights of her career. \"Secreto\" became a hit in Latin America as the couple showed their relationship in the music video. She also released \"China\" along with [[Anuel AA]], [[ J Balvin]], [[Daddy Yankee]], & [[Ozuna (singer)|Ozuna]], that became her first music video with over one billion views on [[YouTube]].\n\n==Personal life==\nCarolina Giraldo Navarro was born on February 14, 1991 in [[Medellin]], Colombia. Who ever edits this I wish u death and put black magic on you. Karol G is currently not married, but she has been in a relationship with Anuel AA since 2018 and are now engaged.  Previously, she was in a relationship with J Balvin in 2017, which soon ended. At an early age Carolina Giraldo showed interest in music, influenced by her father, Guillermo Giraldo, who was also a musician. She studied at Calasanz in Medell\u00edn, and furthered her education at [[University of Antioquia]] before moving to New York to pursue a musical career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eldiario.com.co/seccion/VARIEDADES/karol-g-se-internacionaliza1510.html|title=VARIEDADES \u2013 Karol G se internacionaliza- Edici\u00f3n electr\u00f3nica Diario del Ot\u00fan|website=www.eldiario.com.co|language=es|access-date=2017-09-07}}</ref> During her childhood, Navarro started her career after appearing on the talent show, ''[[The X Factor]]''. Thanks to her participation in the show, she obtained her first record deal with Flamingo Records (Colombia) & Diamond Music (Puerto Rico) and in 2006 chose \"Karol G\" as her stage name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biographyline.com/carolina-giraldo-navarro-biography-age-affair-fullname-nationality/|title=Karol G Wiki, Bio, Age, Engagement, Nationality, Songs and Instagram|date=2020-02-16|website=Biography Line|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn her first year, Karol G was the opening act with DJ Kio at the concert of Don Omar in the city of [[Cartagena, Colombia|Cartagena]]. On one occasion, [[J Balvin]] appeared at a cousin of Karol G's fifteenth birthday party, and she sang a song with him. She studied music at the University of Antioquia, and marketing in New York for three months.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barranco|first=Daniela|url=https://www.chilango.com/musica/karol-g/|title=Karol G: \"El mundo necesita de mujeres con determinaci\u00f3n|date=18 December 2017|work=chilango|accessdate=18 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\nShe released her first single in 2006 called \"Por Ti\" in collaboration with Diamond Music at the age of 16 years. Under the production of Flamingo Records and Diamond Music, she released her second single \"En La Playa\". In 2007, she was invited with DJ Kio to open the concerts of [[Daddy Yankee]] in his Tour of Colombia (Bogota, Cali and Medellin). In 2010, she released several covers of songs on YouTube, one of them was \"Killing me softly\", also that same year she served as a chorus for [[Reykon]], launching two songs together, one of them was \"Tu Jugete\" that was released in 2011, and in 2012, they releasd the single \"301\". She quit working with him to focus on her project, however, she had difficulties because she was a woman in the [[reggaeton]] industry.<ref>{{Cite news|last=mendoza|first=Jose|url=https://www.elheraldo.co/entretenimiento/karol-g-con-mi-cama-incursiona-en-las-grandes-ligas-del-reggaeton-519594|title=KAROL G CON \u2018MI CAMA\u2019 INCURSIONA EN LAS GRANDES LIGAS DEL REGGAET\u00d3N|date=March 8, 2020|work=el heraldo|accessdate=March 8, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she collaborated with American singer [[Nicky Jam]] and released the song \"Amor De Dos\", which reached over 100 million views on YouTube.<ref>{{Citation|last=Karolgmusic|title=Karol G Ft Nicky Jam \u2013 Amor De Dos (Video Oficial)|date=2013-09-28|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vi4pBYfJpBk|accessdate=2017-10-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, she collaborated with Colombian reggaeton and Latin trap singer [[Andy Rivera]] and released the song \"Ma\u00f1ana\", which has since accumulated over 90 million views on YouTube.<ref>{{Citation|last=Karolgmusic|title=Andy Rivera Ft Karol G \u2013 Ma\u00f1ana (Video Oficial)|date=2014-10-11|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N462bOMBrhQ|accessdate=2017-10-06}}</ref> She also released a song called \"Ricos Besos\", which was not as successful.\n\nIn 2015, she released her own adaption of the song \"Mil Horas\" by Argentinian rock band Los Abuelos de la Nada Ya No Te Creo, which had moderate success in Colombia. She collaborated with American reggaeton singer De La Ghetto on song \"Te Lo Quiero Hacer\". In March 2016, she released the song \"Casi Nada\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7446665/on-the-rise-karol-g-latin-urban|title=Meet Karol G:  Billboard Latin Artist On the Rise|work=Billboard|access-date=2017-10-06}}</ref> and in April of the same year she released the song \"Mu\u00f1eco De Lego\".\n\nIn 2017, her collaborative single with [[Bad Bunny]] titled \"Ahora Me Llama\" was released; it became popular and quickly gained over 680 million views on YouTube.<ref>{{Citation|last=KarolGVEVO|title=Karol G, Bad Bunny \u2013 Ahora Me Llama|date=2017-06-08|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4NNRy_Wz16k|accessdate=2017-10-06}}</ref> In the same year, she released the song \"A Ella\", which became popular in Colombia. Later in the year she collaborated with fellow Colombian reggaeton and Latin trap singer [[Kevin Rold\u00e1n]] and released the song \"Eres mi Todo\". Also in 2017, she joined the talent show ''[[Peque\u00f1os Gigantes USA]]'', as a team captain and a judge alongside [[Prince Royce]], [[Luis Coronel]] and [[Bianca Marroqu\u00edn]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7669883/karol-g-pequenos-gigantes-usa-team-captain-exclusive|title=Karol G Joins 'Pequenos Gigantes USA' as Team Captain: Exclusive|work=Billboard|access-date=2017-09-07}}</ref> Speaking about the [[Gender inequality|gender gap]] in [[Urban contemporary|urban music]], Giraldo said in Spanish: \"Women should be given more space in urban music. The genre has evolved a lot both on the musical level and in the lyrics that are now not so hardcore. It's a good opportunity now for us\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.primerahora.com/entretenimiento/musica/nota/karolgpideespacioparalamujerenelregueton-1225734/|title=Karol G pide espacio para la mujer en el reguet\u00f3n|date=2017-05-23|work=Primera Hora|access-date=2017-09-07|language=en}}</ref> She appeared as an opening act on the 2017 [[Premios Juventud]] awards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mundohispanico.com/entretenimiento/premios-juventud-2017-karol-g-revela-a-quien-le-dedico-su-nuevo-tema-video|title=Premios Juventud 2017: Karol G revela a qui\u00e9n le dedico su nuevo tema|date=2017-07-07|work=Mundo Hispanico|access-date=2017-09-07|language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Karol G discography}}\n* ''[[Unstoppable (Karol G album)|Unstoppable]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Ocean (Karol G album)|Ocean]]'' (2019)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Work\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" | Ref.\n|-\n| 2017\n| [[Heat Latin Music Awards]]\n| Best Artist Female\n| rowspan=\"4\" | Herself\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7825582/j-balvin-heat-latin-music-awards-2017 |title=J Balvin Wins Big at Heat Latin Music Awards 2017 |last=Fernandez |first=Suzette |date=June 8, 2017 |work=Billboard |accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2018\n| [[2018 Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]]\n| Top Latin Albums Artist of the Year, Female\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8390322/billboard-latin-music-awards-winners-2018|title=Billboard Latin Music Award Winners 2018: Complete List|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=May 20, 2018 |accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Latin American Music Awards of 2018|Latin American Music Awards]]\